415
47:09.180 --> 47:16.620
if and only if the exclusive or of A and B is equal to the logical and of X and Y.

416
47:16.620 --> 47:23.430
That may be a little bit easier to digest if we express those conditions
in the form of a table as you see right here.

417
47:23.430 --> 47:29.790
In the first column, we have the four possible question pairs, and in the second column we
have the conditions on A and B

418
47:29.790 --> 47:33.420
that are required for
Alice and Bob to win.

419
47:33.420 --> 47:39.570
In the first three cases,
the and of A and Y is zero, so the exclusive or must be equal to zero

420
47:39.570 --> 47:46.890
in order for them to win,
and that's the same thing as saying that A and B must be equal because A and B are bits,
and the fourth case,

421
47:46.890 --> 47:53.460
the and of X and Y is equal
to one and so the exclusive or of A and B must be equal to one in order for Alice and Bob to win

422
47:53.460 --> 47:57.600
and that's the same thing
as saying that A and B must be different.

423
47:57.600 --> 48:07.740
So, that's the CHSH game, and now we can think about
different possible strategies for Alice and Bob and how
well they can do in this game.

424
48:07.740 --> 48:16.260
Let's start by thinking about
deterministic strategies where Alice's answer A is a
function of the question X that she receives, and
likewise, Bob's answer B

425
48:16.260 --> 48:20.220
is a function of the
question Y that he receives.

426
48:20.220 --> 48:26.790
And as it turns out, no
deterministic strategy can possibly win every time.

427
48:26.790 --> 48:33.390
One way to reason that is
simply to go one by one through all of the possible
deterministic strategies and to check that every one of them loses

428
48:33.390 --> 48:37.770
for at least one of the four
possible question pairs.

429
48:37.770 --> 48:46.560
Alice and Bob, each have
four possible functions to choose from, we saw those
four functions in lesson one, so there are 16 possibilities
to check overall.

430
48:46.560 --> 48:53.550
Another way to see that is to
think about the equations here on the screen, we're thinking
about deterministic strategies

431
48:53.550 --> 48:57.120
where A and B are functions
of X and Y respectively.

432
48:57.120 --> 49:05.010
So for example, A of zero
represents Alice's answer when her question X is equal to zero and a of one represents Alice's answer

433
49:05.010 --> 49:09.180
when her question X is equal to one.

434
49:09.180 --> 49:15.450
These are the four equations
that have to be true in order for the winning
conditions to be met in each of the four cases.

435
49:15.450 --> 49:22.350
For example, if X is equal to
zero and Y is equal to zero, then the exclusive or of A
and B must be equal to zero,

436
49:22.350 --> 49:30.090
whereas in the case that X is equal to one and Y is equal to one, the
exclusive or of A and B must be equal to one.

437
49:30.090 --> 49:40.680
One way we can see that
there's no way to choose the functions A and B so that
these equations are all true, is simply to take the exclusive
or of all of the equations.

438
49:40.680 --> 49:47.962
The exclusive or of any
binary value with itself is equal to zero, and so it follows that the exclusive or
of the left-hand sides

439
49:47.962 --> 49:54.720
is equal to zero, that's
because we have two instances of a zero, two instances of a one,

440
49:54.720 --> 49:59.010
two instances of B zero
and two instances of B one.

441
49:59.010 --> 50:07.110
So, xing them all together
gives us the final answer of zero, but if we take the exclusive or of the right hand sides of the equations,

442
50:07.110 --> 50:13.980
we get one not zero. So the four equations
can't possibly all be true, at least one of them has to be wrong

443
50:13.980 --> 50:21.060
and that will lead to a
loss for Alice and Bob in at least one of the four cases.

444
50:21.060 --> 50:28.980
And so it follows because the referee chooses the questions
uniformly that the probability for Alice and Bob to win
using a deterministic strategy

445
50:28.980 --> 50:33.660
is at most three quarters or 75%.

446
50:33.660 --> 50:41.490
The fact that Alice and and Bob can win with probability three quarters is quite easy to see
actually, if Alice and and Bob both answer zero all
the time, for instance,

447
50:41.490 --> 50:46.710
they'll be correct three
out of the four times.

448
50:46.710 --> 50:53.850
So Alice and Bob can't do
any better than winning 75% of the time using a
deterministic strategy.

449
50:53.850 --> 50:57.911
But what about a probabilistic strategy?

450
50:57.911 --> 51:04.950
Well, it turns out that using
a probabilistic strategy can't help them at all, that's because every
probabilistic strategy

451
51:04.950 --> 51:12.000
can alternatively be viewed
as a random selection of a deterministic strategy just like probabilistic
operations can be viewed

452
51:12.000 --> 51:17.760
as random selections of
deterministic operations, as we saw in the first lesson.

453
51:17.760 --> 51:24.840
The average is never
larger than the maximum, so it follows that a
probabilistic strategy doesn't offer any advantage
in terms of winning

454
51:24.840 --> 51:31.860
over a deterministic strategy. This even includes the possibility that Alice and Bob's random
choices are correlated.

455
51:31.860 --> 51:39.420
So, the bottom line is that winning with probability three quarters is the best that Alice
and Bob can possibly do using any classical strategy,

456
51:39.420 --> 51:42.810
whether it's deterministic
or probabilistic.

457
51:42.810 --> 51:49.584
The natural question to ask at this point is whether Alice and Bob can do any better using a quantum strategy,
and in particular

458
51:49.584 --> 51:57.720
if they share an entangled quantum state which they could have repaired
prior to playing the game, can that help them?

459
51:57.720 --> 52:04.800
The answer is yes, it can, and that is the point of the example and that's why it's so interesting.

460
52:04.800 --> 52:12.810
So let's see exactly how
Alice and Bob can do better in this game using entanglement.

